		<div class="postbody">
			
			<h3 class="first">
								<a href="#p37443">Why Ubuntu is a Terrible Distro</a>
			</h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=37443&amp;sid=ddb7fa031a0e0b3a17f7dafccedcc1a7#p37443"><img src="./styles/Carbon/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>			by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=34577&amp;sid=ddb7fa031a0e0b3a17f7dafccedcc1a7">Arameus</a></strong> on Mon Mar 29, 2010 3:19 pm			<br />([msg=37443]see Why Ubuntu is a Terrible Distro[/msg])
			</p>

			
			<div class="content">Now, to be fair, I've only used a few distros: RHEL, Fedora, Debian, and Ubuntu. However I can assure you that by FAR Ubuntu was the absolute worst. Although I have heard many arguments, the most striking annoyance is the use of sudo and the lack of an actual root user. This is massively inconvenient, and it is the reason Ubuntu is almost completely unused in corporate offices and large servers (RHEL dominates this market). Bash scripting and administration of any kind becomes a massive hassle when you are constantly being informed that you have to have administrator privileges (ie you have to use fucking sudo) to do anything. It is only convenient if you are so fucking stupid that you try to do some dumb shit like delete /etc/passwd. In which case, simply dont login as root. Ubuntu sacrifices power for convenience, something for which it should not be forgiven.</div>

			
		</div>

					<dl class="postprofile" id="profile37443">
