	<div id="p48420" class="post bg2">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			
			<h3 >
								<a href="#p48420">Re: Why Ubuntu is a Terrible Distro</a>
			</h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=48420&amp;sid=ddb7fa031a0e0b3a17f7dafccedcc1a7#p48420"><img src="./styles/Carbon/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>			by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=41211&amp;sid=ddb7fa031a0e0b3a17f7dafccedcc1a7">d3v11</a></strong> on Mon Nov 01, 2010 3:08 pm			<br />([msg=48420]see Re: Why Ubuntu is a Terrible Distro[/msg])
			</p>

			
			<div class="content">Ubuntu disables the root account by default for security purposes. Ubuntu attracts a large amount of new Linux users, therefore to keep their box from getting hijacked they disable the root account. This is especially important if you have something like ssh listening on your ports. Having an active root account removes 1/2 the work for a hacker. <br /><br />There are ways around this but many experienced users prefer to keep their root account disabled. Much like myself because I prefer the added security over convenience. <br /><br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: <a href="#" onclick="selectCode(this); return false;">Select all</a></dt><dd><code>sudo passwd root # will create a root password and enable your root account<br />sudo passwd -l root # locks the root account if you later want to disable it<br /><br />sudo -i # this will run your terminal session as root<br /></code></dd></dl><br /><br />problem solved</div>

			<div id="sig48420" class="signature">&quot;The art of war teaches us to rely not on the likelihood of the enemy's not coming, but on our own readiness to receive him; not on the chance of his not attacking, but rather on the fact that we have made our position unassailable.&quot; - Sun Tzu</div>
		</div>

					<dl class="postprofile" id="profile48420">
			<dt>
